WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From LoC + Smithsonian NMAAHC.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:16.000
This is Emily Crosby with the Southern oral history program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:26.000
And I'm conducting this oral history as part of the Civil Rights History Project, sponsored by the Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of American History and Culture

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:29.000
and the American Folklife Center and the Library of Congress.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:40.000
Today is August 23rd, 2013, and we are with Ekwueme Michael Thelwell at his home in Pelham, Massachusetts this morning.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:43.000
And I'm here with John Bishop, who's the videographer.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:47.000
Thank you Professor Delwell for doing the interview with us.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:49.000
Thank you Professor Crosby.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:52.000
I'm happy to do this interview.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:56.000
Can you think of an interviewer I'd be happy to do it with and yourself?

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:58.000
You do me honor, sir.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:05.000
I'm a humble servant of the truth Professor, a humble servant of the truth.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:10.000
Can you tell us about your family growing up in Jamaica?

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:17.000
Yes, I could, if it were necessary.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:25.000
My father as a young man came to the United States and spent some time, some considerable time there.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:29.000
I was quite a legend as I walked through New York, through Harlem.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:34.000
People say, here is sun, here is sun and there are a lot of stories about my father.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:39.000
He was a very dramatic figure.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:45.000
He had a deep boom in laugh, an obvious love of people.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:55.000
He was six foot four, 240 pounds, which in that day on the edge made him a giant.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:02.000
Or he was a professional footballer, lying back today.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:10.000
In this country, he was a motorcycle race, with a motorcycle very big back in the 30s and 40s.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:13.000
And a trick writer.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:20.000
He went back to Jamaica, entered politics, was elected in his constituency.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:26.000
It was very, very popular with the people, look at his generous and kind.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:35.000
And people said if he hadn't died at age of 44, he probably would have been Prime Minister of the country.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:46.000
And there was much speculation that death was a consequence of political conspiracies and wickedness, which is the way people tended to think.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:52.000
My mother was an amazing woman because she brought the thru of herself after my father died.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:03:03.000
I was interested, so a lot of his property was hung up, all kinds of litigation and bureaucracy.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:12.000
And she raised three children, sent us to the best school in the country.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:22.000
My brother became an engineer, went to University of Michigan on an athletic scholarship.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:28.000
And he was six foot five and very black.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:31.000
And he was an excellent athlete.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:37.000
He represented the country and track and field when still a high school boy.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:43.000
And he was an international soccer team when still a high school student.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:50.000
And my mother, who was imperious, had been told such a thing that athletic scholarships existed.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:04:02.000
She collected all his clippings, flew to this country, went to the University of Michigan, walked into the athletic directors office with all these clippings, trying to remember the guy's name.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:07.000
And when she walked over to my brother, I had a scholarship.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:13.000
So my brother arrives here and is running track for Michigan.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:15.000
That lasted one year.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:23.000
Didn't last as long as a year because the academic advisors to the athletic department,

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:30.000
told him that he should major in physical education and become a coach.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:34.000
I mean, here, yeah, this big black guy with a Jamaican accent.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:37.000
Obviously, Physiologist, the major, and he should come.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:38.000
He said, no, he must be able to do mine.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:41.000
That came here to become a civil engineer.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
So, oh, no, no, you got to major in physical education.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:46.000
You can't handle civil engineering.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:54.000
So he told them to kiss his behind and give them back a scholarship and stop competing on his work as way through Michigan.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:05:06.000
On five years later, he graduated with a bachelor's degree in civil engineering, a master's degree in sanitary engineering, and another master's degree in environmental engineering.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:12.000
But I do have this great picture of him running against, as a freshman running against two seniors.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:15.000
They were dead even, so it had to have been the first hurdle.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:27.000
And on one side of him is Len Bonny, who went on to grade fame in the National Football League, and on the other side of him is Herb Adley, who also went on to be a first-rate defensive back, and maybe a hall of fame.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:33.000
And there is my 18-year-old brother right in the middle of them running like hell.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:41.000
Did he miss the video of any regrets about walking away from the athletic?

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:43.000
He never expressed any.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:45.000
Back in see how he couldn't have.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:52.000
Younger brother.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:06:02.000
Actually, his story is really interesting because he was three months premature. He was more or not six months.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:05.000
And only with 20,500 phones.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:13.000
So some members of the family are looking at this little creature saying, he never going to live through him away.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:15.000
You know, dash him away.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:23.000
But my mother fed him with an eyedropper from one of those medicine bottles of associate fed him.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:30.000
And he had to only survive just three and a half-pound birth weight.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:40.000
But he grew to six foot five, and was probably the most phenomenal schoolboy athlete the country ever produced.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:46.000
And also as an excellent environmental engineer, he went back and set up for the government,

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:51.000
the Department of Natural Resources and Conservation in the Jamaican government,

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:59.000
and was a consultant to the United Nations in that field until he prematurely died.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:03.000
And the eyedroboat 60.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:09.000
When you came to this country, did you have much sense of the soil?

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:13.000
Is that something you were thinking about at the time?

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:21.000
I had some sense of the racial circumstances in the country.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:26.000
And I had a deep seat to dread of the South.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:34.000
One of the books that I'd read in Heiss, who was John Oliver Killens' young blood,

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:40.000
which is a very powerful book, had such an effect on me.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:47.000
And also the kind of romances of, was this black guy who used to write all these romances, the The Foxes of Harrow?

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:49.000
Frank Yerby.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:51.000
Okay, here.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:55.000
So I had a serious fear and dread of the South.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:01.000
The first time I went to Louisiana and saw those, what are those,

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:04.000
Spanish, that grown the trees?

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:10.000
My heart fell and I became petrified with fear, just the image of the Spanish.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:16.000
I mean, I never, other sense of the South, I got from Faulkner.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:24.000
And then in addition to which, I got to the United States, got to hold university.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:29.000
In September 1959.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:33.000
And the spring of 1966, the student freedom rights happened.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:39.000
So I've often claimed that I arrived in this country and touched off the student movement in the South.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:42.000
I arrived when I touched the top.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:47.000
People have tended to contest that.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:51.000
It advised people, misguided people, have tended to contest that.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:55.000
And obviously you arrived, it's very, very important.

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:58.000
How did you come to Howard?

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:01.000
The sequential file, as you have this say.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:03.000
How did I come to Howard?

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:04.000
Yeah.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.000
And rather not say.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:09.000
Okay.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:14.000
My formal answer to that question is, I wanted to go to a black school,

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:20.000
so I could be immersed in black culture and develop an African-American perspective on the world.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:23.000
That's my official position.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:29.000
The real position was, as we're considered, the American industrial corporation.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:36.000
And a young economist came in, the other master's degree in economy from Howard University, Conor and Pain.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:42.000
He was very elegant, very dark guy, spoken a very affected way.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:49.000
And naturally I gravitated to him because here's this genuine intellectual black mind.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:54.000
And he said, you got to go to Howard University, Washington DC, there are nine women forever men.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:59.000
And every male student at Howard, have at least three or four girlfriends at the same time.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:02.000
I said, that's all I want to know.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:05.000
That's the real reason I went to Howard.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:07.000
You needed those cards?

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:08.000
I beg your pardon?

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:10.000
I said, you needed those cards?

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:13.000
No, I didn't forget. I needed them, but I wouldn't hurt.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:15.000
Not going to throw them down.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:24.000
There's an evil proverb, which says, only a fool spits out the tender muscle that a kind God places between his lips.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:27.000
And then you won that kind of fool.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:32.000
No, man. I've been called everything with a child, a guy, and a Republican.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:36.000
And you know, ain't nobody ever called me a fool.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:39.000
So what was Howard like for you? What was your life?

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:41.000
Amazing.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:51.000
That is the best decision anybody ever made for the wrong reasons.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:57.000
You know, anything people want to know about a student experience at Howard,

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:00.000
they can read and comment because they're great for revolution.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:01.000
Who was at Howard with us?

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:04.000
As was Courtland Cox, as was Charlie Cobb.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:08.000
There was a whole host of us since the group came through Howard.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:11.000
And that's not accidental.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:15.000
The first thing is Howard was very strategically placed.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:22.000
Being in the nation's capital, and as you know, they're only federally supported black institution in the country,

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:30.000
which created interest in political problems because the people who control the whole university budget were also done congressmen,

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:35.000
all dixacrites, all white supremacists, and segregationists.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:42.000
So that for example, in the four years I was here, and a member of NAG.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:45.000
NAG was never recognized student organization.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:48.000
The NAACP was a recognized student organization.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:52.000
The French club was a recognized student organization.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:57.000
The German club was a recognized student organization, but NAG was not.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:00.000
Are we following that very distressing?

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:08.000
When it turns out that President Mordecai Johnson and then the President and the neighbor knew exactly what they were doing.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:12.000
So when they went to get their budgets from Congress, and people say,

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:16.000
all of them are liberals, run around the place, beans are disruptive.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:19.000
Can you control them?

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:27.000
You say, but Mr. Congressmen, Mr. Senator, I've scrutinized the student organizations at Howard University very carefully.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:33.000
There's no non-violent action group there, and such an organization doesn't exist as far as our record show.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:38.000
It must be young people from Georgetown and Georgetown and Washington, and those are the schools.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:48.000
But it gave us an excellent issue around which to organize,

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:53.000
because every year we went to the large campaign to get NAACP recognized.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:13:04.000
And I had to tell you, in my own case, I was not even aware of the strategy of protecting us that a university president was doing.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:12.000
So we thought of an expression of whole-backedness and reaction-nearness that it wouldn't recognize us.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:17.000
I was struggled, and even students who weren't very politically active,

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:21.000
who was well-for-turned-it-to-greetly to students, when we started saying,

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:26.000
oh, come this non-violent action group is not recognized, they turned out in demonstrate enough, fear.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:32.000
The student government would make statements that would all be recognized by the university health very firm,

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:37.000
or they never recognized, so it didn't formally and officially exist.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:41.000
What point did you understand what they were doing?

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:44.000
Long after I had left.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:50.000
But, honest, it didn't have to be grateful for the issue to organize our own.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:55.000
We could get the school year started with a political confrontation with the administration.

