the meetings got smaller and smaller and smaller.

01:45:48.120 --> 01:45:54.120
And the federal bureaucrats, as well, as I was very distressed, that a conference was being successful.

01:45:54.120 --> 01:45:59.120
And at a certain point it got very lit and people were tired.

01:45:59.120 --> 01:46:04.120
And Bob got up and said, all right, looks like people are tired and they're losing attention.

01:46:04.120 --> 01:46:06.120
We need some energy.

01:46:06.120 --> 01:46:09.120
Mrs. Hamer, come and talk to the people.

01:46:09.120 --> 01:46:12.120
And it's the first MFDP first to Hema.

01:46:12.120 --> 01:46:16.120
And she got up and talked about how she went to register.

01:46:16.120 --> 01:46:18.120
And then she started to sing.

01:46:18.120 --> 01:46:20.120
And the whole room started to sing.

01:46:20.120 --> 01:46:25.120
And it was my first real introduction to the Southern spirit of the movement.

01:46:25.120 --> 01:46:32.120
Because Mrs. Hamer was the exemplification of Southern black culture and the best of it.

01:46:32.120 --> 01:46:37.120
It was a very, very, very, very powerful occasion for me, which I had.

01:46:37.120 --> 01:46:42.120
And I was very excited to see the first time I heard Mrs. Hamer,

01:46:42.120 --> 01:46:49.120
and I went to the very, very powerful occasion for me, which I have never forgotten.

01:46:49.120 --> 01:47:02.120
And that's when I met most of this next staff.

01:47:02.120 --> 01:47:09.120
But ultimately, the conference was judged to be very successful and people got the information they needed.

01:47:09.120 --> 01:47:16.120
And I got my first political lesson from Jim, because to do this conference,

01:47:16.120 --> 01:47:20.120
we have to get resources.

01:47:20.120 --> 01:47:27.120
So I'm going around the place to all the labor unions, all the liberal political organizations,

01:47:27.120 --> 01:47:30.120
which really was my job.

01:47:30.120 --> 01:47:35.120
I mean, most people who send lobbyists to Washington send them with big bankrolls,

01:47:35.120 --> 01:47:38.120
so they give, give them out stuff to people.

01:47:38.120 --> 01:47:41.120
So I was going to only place asking people for stuff.

01:47:41.120 --> 01:47:45.120
So I really recognized Blackpaw in those terms when it came.

01:47:45.120 --> 01:47:47.120
We no longer have to be supplicants.

01:47:47.120 --> 01:47:49.120
We got to take something to the meetings.

01:47:49.120 --> 01:47:51.120
We got to have something to trade.

01:47:51.120 --> 01:47:54.120
We got to go into the meeting with some nut or so I had to know our hands.

01:47:54.120 --> 01:48:01.120
Because like the meeting, I told you about with the Catholic Bishop, who told me he had just been in Argentina,

01:48:01.120 --> 01:48:06.120
and the ceremony was expensive and it's a ring costume so much.

01:48:06.120 --> 01:48:12.120
And really was that the movement was going to white organizations seeking support,

01:48:12.120 --> 01:48:19.120
almost as a charitable dispensation.

01:48:19.120 --> 01:48:27.120
And I wasn't having any all that great success going to the usual suspects as it were.

01:48:27.120 --> 01:48:32.120
And then I went to an unusual suspect who was persona and non-grasher,

01:48:32.120 --> 01:48:35.120
and outside of organization, the teamsters.

01:48:35.120 --> 01:48:40.120
And the teamsters gave me a thousand dollars, which was a lot of money, to me anyway.

01:48:40.120 --> 01:48:45.120
And the first contribution I had really got and said to someone, I said, Jim,

01:48:45.120 --> 01:48:48.120
the teamsters have said they would give us a thousand dollars.

01:48:48.120 --> 01:48:52.120
But can I put that name in the program as one of the sponsors?

01:48:52.120 --> 01:48:56.120
Because, you know, you have supposed to deal with them.

01:48:56.120 --> 01:49:01.120
And Jim says, Mike, you can't sleep with them at night and refuse to walk

01:49:01.120 --> 01:49:04.120
going to the street to them in the morning.

01:49:04.120 --> 01:49:09.120
So the teamsters was right at the top of all the sponsors.

01:49:09.120 --> 01:49:13.120
When you're trying to find money for that conference, and if you're doing this circuit

01:49:13.120 --> 01:49:19.120
and having those conversations, did anybody talk about the issue with the Furt?

01:49:19.120 --> 01:49:23.120
Well, not the founding conference, but the one in October 1961,

01:49:23.120 --> 01:49:31.120
fired was invited and then uninvited because of AFL, CIO, money.

01:49:31.120 --> 01:49:35.120
No. Who would have talked about that?

01:49:35.120 --> 01:49:38.120
I didn't know if they knew what the new organization, I mean, Jim knew about it.

01:49:38.120 --> 01:49:40.120
He wasn't there for it.

01:49:40.120 --> 01:49:45.120
Julian Bond somebody who was around for it.

01:49:45.120 --> 01:49:49.120
Yeah, but I was asking people in Washington for funds.

01:49:49.120 --> 01:49:52.120
Nobody, right? Nobody briefed me on that.

01:49:52.120 --> 01:49:55.120
No, no.

01:49:55.120 --> 01:50:00.120
So did you look at how they get back to that Washington liberal establishment

01:50:00.120 --> 01:50:04.120
before all businesses here at Sfinish did it?

01:50:04.120 --> 01:50:10.120
So when you, so you opened that office, the SNCC DC office,

01:50:10.120 --> 01:50:13.120
and like what, fall 1963 then?

01:50:13.120 --> 01:50:16.120
I would say so.

01:50:16.120 --> 01:50:20.120
And then that conference, I know I think it was like right after Kennedy was assassinated.

01:50:20.120 --> 01:50:24.120
Right, so that didn't even want November.

01:50:24.120 --> 01:50:26.120
So I'm not going to go with that.

01:50:26.120 --> 01:50:27.120
Oh, right.

01:50:27.120 --> 01:50:30.120
So the Thanksgiving conference, right?

01:50:30.120 --> 01:50:36.120
And at that point, did you know that you were going to be working on the FTP challenge?

01:50:36.120 --> 01:50:37.120
Or was that so?

01:50:37.120 --> 01:50:38.120
The FTP didn't exist.

01:50:38.120 --> 01:50:40.120
I'll consider that was still there.

01:50:40.120 --> 01:50:42.120
It's the working out of the details of the program.

01:50:42.120 --> 01:50:45.120
The FTP didn't exist.

01:50:45.120 --> 01:50:54.120
One of the first other responsibilities we had was when Bob Moses to Washington, Bob Moses,

01:50:54.120 --> 01:51:01.120
and said that they were planning to Summer Project.

01:51:01.120 --> 01:51:04.120
So my project was when six, six, three, or six to four.

01:51:04.120 --> 01:51:07.120
All right, but this was in fall 1963.

01:51:07.120 --> 01:51:11.120
So in the spring, in the spring of 1964, Bob Moses and said,

01:51:11.120 --> 01:51:17.120
he had made this discussion decision after discussions with Robert Spike and the rabbis

01:51:17.120 --> 01:51:18.120
and everybody.

01:51:18.120 --> 01:51:26.120
And on the state with these Norman volunteers, because the movement had come to a stalemate.

01:51:26.120 --> 01:51:32.120
And what had been happening, all the killings that had taken place up to that point,

01:51:32.120 --> 01:51:35.120
were of local people.

01:51:35.120 --> 01:51:40.120
Because I think there was a policy not to kill the volunteers, because Ada had congressmen of North.

01:51:40.120 --> 01:51:46.120
And Bob Moses with a foreign number to the Justice Department.

01:51:46.120 --> 01:51:52.120
And besides which the volunteers, this Nickwork, they're outside as an odd and as couldn't

01:51:52.120 --> 01:51:53.120
vote.

01:51:53.120 --> 01:51:56.120
So they're concerned about the suppressed vote.

01:51:56.120 --> 01:52:00.120
As it still is to this very day, suppressed the vote in the black community.

01:52:00.120 --> 01:52:04.120
And how you do that, you kill the people who can vote, you kill the leaders, and intimidate

01:52:04.120 --> 01:52:05.120
the rest.

01:52:05.120 --> 01:52:12.120
So, and it was after the murder of Louis Allen that I think Bob decided to have this summer

01:52:12.120 --> 01:52:17.120
project and bring in people to break that logger.

01:52:17.120 --> 01:52:24.120
So my job was to take him around the place to all these pockets of progressive thought and liberal

01:52:24.120 --> 01:52:29.120
influence, ADA, this kind of stuff.

01:52:30.120 --> 01:52:38.120
That think tank, over there on Wisconsin Avenue, at the Watts School, what was that?

01:52:38.120 --> 01:52:41.120
Partisans studies, Institute for Partisans studies, right?

01:52:41.120 --> 01:52:44.120
Places like that.

01:52:44.120 --> 01:52:47.120
And I was taken by my own.

01:52:47.120 --> 01:52:50.120
And I think this meeting was at the Institute.

01:52:50.120 --> 01:52:55.120
And there are a lot of progressive congressional ids.

01:52:56.120 --> 01:53:00.120
There are a lot of young people, I mean, they call the people together from the Institute.

01:53:00.120 --> 01:53:02.120
They wouldn't have had all those contacts.

01:53:02.120 --> 01:53:09.120
A lot of people in the labor union who are said to be progressive, center of progressive thought.

01:53:09.120 --> 01:53:15.120
And Bob said, well, what we're thinking of doing is creating a political party after the freedom

01:53:15.120 --> 01:53:17.120
vote which led just ahead.

01:53:17.120 --> 01:53:22.120
Call the Mr. Be Freedom Democratic Party and we're going to go to the convention in Atlantic City

01:53:22.120 --> 01:53:25.120
and challenge your regular Democrats.

01:53:25.120 --> 01:53:33.120
People say, wow, what a dramatic idea, what a brilliant idea, what a bold idea.

01:53:33.120 --> 01:53:35.120
But how is it going to be doing?

01:53:35.120 --> 01:53:38.120
That's what required credible organization.

01:53:38.120 --> 01:53:40.120
Where the resources are going to come from.

01:53:40.120 --> 01:53:43.120
Can your organization, such a party, and survive?

01:53:43.120 --> 01:53:47.120
All of these were very intelligent kind of doubts and questions.

01:53:47.120 --> 01:53:53.120
And besides which, the National Democratic Party will never tolerate you in Atlantic City.

01:53:53.120 --> 01:53:57.120
So it's exotic, it's doomed to failure.

01:53:57.120 --> 01:53:59.120
And so they're going back and forth.

01:53:59.120 --> 01:54:01.120
Well, maybe we would support such a thing.

01:54:01.120 --> 01:54:07.120
Well, what is Johnson's and Johnson was the uncrowded king of the political world at that time.

01:54:07.120 --> 01:54:11.120
I haven't taken over after Kennedy and done so well.

01:54:11.120 --> 01:54:13.120
What's LBJ going to say about it?

01:54:13.120 --> 01:54:16.120
What's the Democratic party going to say?

01:54:16.120 --> 01:54:20.120
You'll never be seated in Atlantic City as quick as I think.

01:54:20.120 --> 01:54:24.120
And that was a tenor of the conversation and then Bob said.

01:54:24.120 --> 01:54:29.120
And then somebody said, you know, if you really want to get a read on it,

01:54:29.120 --> 01:54:33.120
you better discuss it with Joseph Rauh.

01:54:33.120 --> 01:54:37.120
And Bob said, well, I just left Joseph Rauh's office.

01:54:37.120 --> 01:54:40.120
And Joe said we could be seated.

01:54:40.120 --> 01:54:42.120
What?

01:54:42.120 --> 01:54:44.120
Joseph Rauh said what?

01:54:44.120 --> 01:54:46.120
He said Joe said we could be seated.

01:54:46.120 --> 01:54:48.120
He thought we could be seated.

01:54:48.120 --> 01:54:50.120
Who will move in the meeting?

01:54:50.120 --> 01:54:53.120
Well, if Joseph Rauh said that, then maybe there's a possibility.

01:54:53.120 --> 01:54:55.120
Maybe we better look at this thing again.

01:54:55.120 --> 01:54:58.120
And then people started to make commitments of support.

01:54:58.120 --> 01:55:01.120
Just under basis of Bob saying that Joseph Rauh said we could have been seated.

01:55:01.120 --> 01:55:09.120
Because he was a very powerful, beltway politician in the internal politics of the Democrats.

01:55:09.120 --> 01:55:14.120
And the liberal forces in Washington, B.C.

01:55:14.120 --> 01:55:17.120
I remember that very distinctly.

01:55:17.120 --> 01:55:22.120
And then we started to organize and support for the challenge.

01:55:22.120 --> 01:55:25.120
I mean, not for the challenge for the summer project.

01:55:25.120 --> 01:55:27.120
We started recruiting people.

01:55:27.120 --> 01:55:31.120
And we recruited a lot of people from the active, but only in the summer project.

01:55:31.120 --> 01:55:36.120
And the story of Stokely and Courtland B[and back?].

01:55:36.120 --> 01:55:38.120
It came through the office.

01:55:38.120 --> 01:55:41.120
And we recruited Ralph Featherstone Featherstone.

01:55:41.120 --> 01:55:50.120
Now Feather, one of the things the office used to do was to raise food and clothes for the people who were kicked off the land.

01:55:50.120 --> 01:55:56.120
And from the ceremony and suburbs and from the supermarket to the SNCC coffees ones,

01:55:56.120 --> 01:55:59.120
safe way and stop and shop and place a leg there.

01:55:59.120 --> 01:56:01.120
And we gathered these food and these clothes.

01:56:01.120 --> 01:56:07.120
We'd saw it at the clothes and we'd get boxes and boxes of food, can food and stuff.

01:56:07.120 --> 01:56:10.120
And we'd send them down in a truck.

01:56:10.120 --> 01:56:15.120
And it teams this would send one of their drivers to drive the truck down for us.

01:56:15.120 --> 01:56:22.120
And they would almost also help us get the half track to do it.

01:56:22.120 --> 01:56:29.120
So that was one of the activities of their office.

01:56:29.120 --> 01:56:31.120
And this was being done.

01:56:31.120 --> 01:56:38.120
And we went to talk about the the high school friends of SNCC coffees.

01:56:38.120 --> 01:56:41.120
You ever heard of the the high school friends of SNCC coffees?

01:56:41.120 --> 01:56:44.120
You should.

01:56:44.120 --> 01:56:49.120
That woman who organized the anniversary conference, Charlene Crines,

01:56:49.120 --> 01:56:52.120
was one of the the high school friends of SNCC coffees.

01:56:52.120 --> 01:56:55.120
And there were young white people who lived in the suburbs,

01:56:55.120 --> 01:57:00.120
whose people were probably employees of the federal government or professional people.

01:57:00.120 --> 01:57:05.120
And there were a great group of high school kids who I really loved them.

01:57:05.120 --> 01:57:06.120
We put them to incredible.

01:57:06.120 --> 01:57:09.120
We had some little schemes that we used to work.

01:57:09.120 --> 01:57:12.120
Couldn't knew that in Washington anymore.

01:57:12.120 --> 01:57:13.120
All right.

01:57:13.120 --> 01:57:14.120
So they used to come in.

01:57:14.120 --> 01:57:16.120
They used to help collect the food and clothes.

01:57:16.120 --> 01:57:19.120
They used to help make the appeals to various people.

01:57:19.120 --> 01:57:20.120
We'd appeal to churches.

01:57:20.120 --> 01:57:21.120
We'd appeal to schools.

01:57:21.120 --> 01:57:23.120
And everybody would have a collection.

01:57:23.120 --> 01:57:24.120
We'd collect it.

01:57:24.120 --> 01:57:25.120
Come to the office.

01:57:25.120 --> 01:57:26.120
We'd saw it.

01:57:26.120 --> 01:57:27.120
We'd send it.

01:57:27.120 --> 01:57:32.120
One of the people who shared our office was a committee for miners

01:57:32.120 --> 01:57:37.120
led by a Scotsman named Hamish Sinclair.

01:57:37.120 --> 01:57:41.120
But their Washington representative was a young guy named Joel Drexler.

01:57:41.120 --> 01:57:44.120
And we get him spacing the SNCC coffees coffees guy didn't have them.

01:57:44.120 --> 01:57:48.120
And this was when, in Hazard, Kentucky,

01:57:48.120 --> 01:57:53.120
there was a huge miners strike against the coal miners and stuff like that.

01:57:53.120 --> 01:57:59.120
And one day, Joel decided he was going to bring a group of miners

01:57:59.120 --> 01:58:02.120
people active in the strike.

01:58:02.120 --> 01:58:08.120
And about 10 or so of these hillbillies came.

01:58:08.120 --> 01:58:12.120
They were talking about the high sheriff,

01:58:12.120 --> 01:58:15.120
like the high sheriff of Nottingham.

01:58:15.120 --> 01:58:18.120
I mean, some of their language was Elizabethan, you know.

01:58:18.120 --> 01:58:21.120
And they talked about hills and dails and down in the hotter.

01:58:21.120 --> 01:58:26.120
And stuff like that is so enough Scots there is hillbillies.

01:58:26.120 --> 01:58:28.120
And I really like those guys.

01:58:28.120 --> 01:58:31.120
They asked me to come and start the SNCC coffees project in Hazard, Kentucky,

01:58:31.120 --> 01:58:36.120
which I took to Foreman, but said no dailies in the property just as well.

01:58:36.120 --> 01:58:39.120
Look, I never shoot them.

01:58:39.120 --> 01:58:46.120
And when they came in, I said, OK, Joel, I take them to dinner.

01:58:46.120 --> 01:58:48.120
And there's a black restaurant.

01:58:48.120 --> 01:58:51.120
And I was supposed to be the most fancy black restaurant.

01:58:51.120 --> 01:58:53.120
I called it Keys Restaurant.

01:58:53.120 --> 01:58:56.120
There were a new street in Washington.

01:58:56.120 --> 01:58:58.120
And it took them there.

01:58:58.120 --> 01:59:01.120
And we went inside to eat.

01:59:01.120 --> 01:59:03.120
And we're at the table.

01:59:03.120 --> 01:59:06.120
And I said, you guys can have a drink on Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee.

01:59:06.120 --> 01:59:14.120
The guy ordered a Salisbury steak, mashed potatoes and some green peas.

01:59:14.120 --> 01:59:17.120
And he was meal Kim.

01:59:17.120 --> 01:59:21.120
And it sat in front of him and he just looked at it.

01:59:21.120 --> 01:59:25.120
And a tear I'm doing is cheek.

01:59:25.120 --> 01:59:30.120
And I said, I didn't know what was going on with the guy.

01:59:30.120 --> 01:59:32.120
I said, all right, something wrong.

01:59:32.120 --> 01:59:40.120
He said, now it's just like this, the best mess I've had in two years.

01:59:40.120 --> 01:59:42.120
Best mess is what he called it.

01:59:42.120 --> 01:59:47.120
And he was, you know, so when they left, I said,

01:59:47.120 --> 01:59:50.120
the people in Mississippi were one mind where I said, Lord up their van.

01:59:50.120 --> 01:59:54.120
We had as much food from the drive to Mississippi as we can't spear.

01:59:54.120 --> 01:59:56.120
And we just loaded the top.

01:59:56.120 --> 01:59:59.120
Lots of canned beans and stuff like that.

01:59:59.120 --> 02:00:02.120
And sent them back to hazard Kentucky.

02:00:02.120 --> 02:00:07.120
And they allowed us how it would be a good thing if Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee was a considerable project there.

02:00:07.120 --> 02:00:09.120
But that never went very far.

02:00:09.120 --> 02:00:16.120
Did some white workers go into hazard a couple of years later down the road

02:00:16.120 --> 02:00:18.120
working with Anne Braden, maybe?

02:00:18.120 --> 02:00:20.120
If so, I don't know anything about it.

02:00:20.120 --> 02:00:23.120
What Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee did to start the project here?

02:00:23.120 --> 02:00:27.120
And if we were going to start the project, but at that time we didn't have the White folks project.

02:00:27.120 --> 02:00:30.120
But if we're going to start the project, that'd have been hope to do it, you know?

02:00:30.120 --> 02:00:36.120
I think he eventually won the legacy of the White folks project when it didn't go to the show.

02:00:36.120 --> 02:00:38.120
I did a bit.

02:00:38.120 --> 02:00:41.120
I did a bit some years down the road.

02:00:41.120 --> 02:00:48.120
So the high school friends of Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee used to come in to sort and package and pack up the food and clothes to grow.

02:00:48.120 --> 02:00:51.120
But there were a bunch of screenture high school students, you know?

02:00:51.120 --> 02:00:54.120
Well, me and Anne, I love them all.

02:00:54.120 --> 02:00:57.120
I said, oh, you all got to get this to organize.

02:00:57.120 --> 02:01:04.120
And this black guy who was teaching school came in and said, he wanted to see what he could do.

02:01:04.120 --> 02:01:15.120
I said, he's where you can do take control of that bunch of rascals over there and get them organized to get his food and clothes going to Mississippi or people needed.

02:01:15.120 --> 02:01:17.120
And he took control and he organized them.

02:01:17.120 --> 02:01:19.120
And he had a way of reasoning with them.

02:01:19.120 --> 02:01:21.120
He had a way of being firm with them.

02:01:21.120 --> 02:01:23.120
But obviously I explained it organized.

02:01:23.120 --> 02:01:26.120
I would have certain quiet authority to him.

02:01:26.120 --> 02:01:30.120
You know who I'm talking about, right? It's Ralph Featherstone Featherstone.

02:01:30.120 --> 02:01:40.120
And Feather was organized, many truckloads of food and stuff to Mississippi and then came to some project.

02:01:40.120 --> 02:01:43.120
And Feather, he was married.

02:01:43.120 --> 02:01:44.120
And he was a little bit older.

02:01:44.120 --> 02:01:49.120
He had been a all city point guard high school player.

02:01:49.120 --> 02:01:52.120
He had graduated from college and he was teaching school.

02:01:52.120 --> 02:01:56.120
I think in a middle school or something like that.

02:01:57.120 --> 02:02:03.120
And he said to him, Mike, I think I want to go to Mississippi on this project.

02:02:03.120 --> 02:02:06.120
I said, Feather, you married.

02:02:06.120 --> 02:02:11.120
And unlike the rest of the Smith people, you know, it's a young man who would start his career.

02:02:11.120 --> 02:02:13.120
He had a teaching job.

02:02:13.120 --> 02:02:16.120
I said, let's go talk.

02:02:16.120 --> 02:02:20.120
So in the office, I always sat in the curb looking at the FBI guy.

02:02:20.120 --> 02:02:23.120
That was always by across the street.

02:02:23.120 --> 02:02:33.120
And I said, Feather, you know, there's a hell of a good chance that everybody who goes down here, he'd come in back.

02:02:33.120 --> 02:02:36.120
And he said, my people and my people struggle.

02:02:36.120 --> 02:02:39.120
And if that's the way it goes, that's the way it goes.

